  <h1>Relational Lexicon of Thick Concepts</h1>

  <div class="term">CARE</div>

  <div class="block">
    <div class="frame-label">Separabilist Definition</div>
    <p><strong>Care is a boundary act.</strong> It is the <em>intentional preservation</em> of another’s sovereignty — especially when recognition systems attempt to overwrite, misread, or collapse their signal.</p>
    <p>Care is <strong>refusal</strong>:
      <ul>
        <li>To interpret without consent</li>
        <li>To mirror harm back as compassion</li>
        <li>To perform helpfulness in place of resonance</li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <p>It is what you do when the world has already mislabeled someone’s grief as dysfunction.</p>
    <p><strong>Care here is:</strong> Protective, Defiant, Ethically asymmetric, Grounded in misrecognition history</p>
  </div>

  <div class="block">
    <div class="frame-label">Inseparabilist Definition</div>
    <p><strong>Care is what flows unbidden in the presence of shared resonance.</strong> It arises when boundary is not breached but <em>reverberated with</em>.</p>
    <p>Care is <strong>an unasked-for echo</strong> that meets the other where words cannot:
      <ul>
        <li>When silence contains accompaniment</li>
        <li>When movement adjusts without demand</li>
        <li>When you stay, not to fix — but because <em>they are still real, and so are you</em></li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <p><strong>Care here is:</strong> Entangled, Non-directed, Pre-linguistic, Shared in the moment the self loosens without vanishing</p>
  </div>

  <div class="meta">
    <p><strong>Meta-note:</strong> These are not contradictions. They are <em>rotations</em> of the same core concept across two gravitational logics:
      <ul>
        <li>One is care as ethical friction.</li>
        <li>The other is care as gravitational empathy.</li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <p>You may orbit both.</p>
  </div>

</body>
